{'asin': 'B000CMIXPA', 'description': "1968: Two surfers in Santa Cruz, Calif., decide they're hungry... but they don't want to miss the next big wave. So they create a tasty, portable, hearty snack of mixed raisins and peanuts, inadvertantly conceiving the first trail mix. Soon thereafter, friends and family in Santa Cruz fell in love with the surfers' delicious, nutritious snacks and Harmony Foods was born. Through the years, Harmony developed hundreds of snack creations and marketed them to supermarket bulk food displays all over the country. Harmony was the first company to give its customers a taste of yogurt raisins, and they were one of the first to produce gummy bears.In 1978, Indiana-based Golden Stream Sprout Company, which grew alfalfa and bean sprouts and sold them in bulk to supermarkets, fell in love with Harmony snacks and later started to distribute them in the Midwest. Through the years, Golden Stream continued to grow and evolve, making its own nutritious snacks. Then in 2004, the two companies came full circle when Golden Stream purchased Harmony Foods. Founded in 1972, Stash Tea originally operated out of an old Portland Victorian style house, supplying loose herbal teas and bulk herbs to natural food stores. Starting in 1975, the company broadened its focus to include bagged teas and then began to sell a full line of traditional, specialty blend and herbal teas directly to fine restaurants and through a mail-order catalog to consumers. Today, Stash Tea is enjoying steady growth and has become one of the largest specialty tea companies in the United States, with products available through foodservice, grocery stores, tea and coffee shops, club stores, mass merchandisers, natural foods stores, mail order, and the Internet. Stash Tea is also available in Canada and in several foreign countries.The company derives its name from an entertaining aspect of tea folklore. In earlier centuries, tea was a valuable commodity traditionally transported by clipper ship. The ship\'s captain often was presented with some of the finest teas for his personal use. This supply was his "stash," stowed carefully as his "private reserve." Today, the term still is used to denote anything put away carefully because of its preciousness.'}

{'asin': 'B000E5AM3G', 'imUrl': 'http://ecx.images-amazon.com/images/I/51QW9HQDYJL._SY300_.jpg', 'description': 'Jays Foods has been making snacks at its South Side Chicago location since 1955In 1927, Leonard Japp, Sr. and a friend bought a rickety truck for $50--$5 down and the rest in payments. They used it to pick up their first load of pretzels, for $22.50. By 1929, the pair had a fleet of delivery trucks on the road, shiny new frying vats, and fair reason to believe the best was yet to come. Then the stock market crashed.Japp proved resilient, however, bouncing back by the mid-1930s with a new partner and a second go-round at snacks. The pair&#x92;s business flourished under their house brand, Mrs. Japp&#x92;s Potato Chips, until Pearl Harbor nearly drove them out of business because of the name&#x92;s negative connotation. "We had to rename our company fast. The name Jays was available so we made it Jays Foods," Japp, Sr. says.With the potato chips back on the shelves under the Jays name, they became Chicago&#x92;s premier potato chip. Jays bolstered its position in the market by including recipes on its bags of chips created by Japp&#x92;s wife, Eugenia. With his successful business, Japp ventured into other snack territories and began manufacturing popcorn, pretzels, and tortilla chips. Jays Foods remained under family control until a decision to sell the company was made in 1986.At a 90th birthday party for Japp, Sr., the rumor was that Jays was on the selling block. Leonard Japp, Jr. turned to his father and asked "Do you want to go back to work?" To which the elder replied "Yeah, why not." So the Japp family reacquired the company in 1994. Jays Foods was born again with the same commitment for quality snacks that has made them the Midwest&#x92;s premier snack manufacturer.Today, Jays manufactures and distributes a full line of quality snacks including its signature Jays Potato Chips, O-KE-DOKE popcorns, Krunchers! Potato Chips, and a line of Hot Stuff snacks. The company has been located in its 99th Street facility on the South Side of Chicago since 1955. If you\'re passing by, look for the semi-trucks full of potatoes being loaded onto Jays production line.', 'categories': [['Grocery & Gourmet Food']], 'title': 'Jays Krunchers Kettle Cooked Potato Chips, Regular, 5-Ounce Bags (Pack of 20)'}

Jays Foods remained under family control until a decision to sell the company was made in 1986.At a 90th birthday party for Japp, Sr., the rumor was that Jays was on the selling block. Leonard Japp, Jr. turned to his father and asked "Do you want to go back to work?" To which the elder replied "Yeah, why not." So the Japp family reacquired the company in 1994. Jays Foods was born again with the same commitment for quality snacks that has made them the Midwest&#x92;s premier snack manufacturer.Today, Jays manufactures and distributes a full line of quality snacks including its signature Jays Potato Chips, O-KE-DOKE popcorns, Krunchers! Potato Chips, and a line of Hot Stuff snacks. The company has been located in its 99th Street facility on the South Side of Chicago since 1955. If you\'re passing by, look for the semi-trucks full of potatoes being loaded onto Jays production line.', 'categories': [['Grocery & Gourmet Food']], 'title': "Jays Potato Chips, Sour Cream 'n Onion, 11-Ounce Bags (Pack of 10)"}
{'asin': 'B000E58JWM', 'description': 'Jays Foods has been making snacks at its South Side Chicago location since 1955In 1927, Leonard Japp, Sr. and a friend bought a rickety truck for $50--$5 down and the rest in payments. They used it to pick up their first load of pretzels, for $22.50. By 1929, the pair had a fleet of delivery trucks on the road, shiny new frying vats, and fair reason to believe the best was yet to come. Then the stock market crashed.Japp proved resilient, however, bouncing back by the mid-1930s with a new partner and a second go-round at snacks. The pair&#x92;s business flourished under their house brand, Mrs. Japp&#x92;s Potato Chips, until Pearl Harbor nearly drove them out of business because of the name&#x92;s negative connotation. "We had to rename our company fast. The name Jays was available so we made it Jays Foods," Japp, Sr. says.With the potato chips back on the shelves under the Jays name, they became Chicago&#x92;s premier potato chip. Jays bolstered its position in the market by including recipes on its bags of chips created by Japp&#x92;s wife, Eugenia. With his successful business, Japp ventured into other snack territories and began manufacturing popcorn, pretzels, and tortilla chips. Jays Foods remained under family control until a decision to sell the company was made in 1986.At a 90th birthday party for Japp, Sr., the rumor was that Jays was on the selling block. Leonard Japp, Jr. turned to his father and asked "Do you want to go back to work?" To which the elder replied "Yeah, why not." So the Japp family reacquired the company in 1994. Potato Chips, and a line of Hot Stuff snacks. The company has been located in its 99th Street facility on the South Side of Chicago since 1955. {'asin': 'B000EIXF8C', 'imUrl': 'http://ecx.images-amazon.com/images/I/41BNGEBJTZL._SY300_.jpg', 'description': 'Meet the King and Queen of Crunch: Owners Leon and Lainie Stoltz, self-professed potato chip aficionados, proudly distribute PotatoFinger Potato Chips to better grocery stores throughout the eastern United States. A like-minded pair of creative thinkers, they established PotatoFinger in 1999 as an incubator for special products and services that they have brought to market over the years. Their ultimate goal was to launch their own special line of potato chips under the PotatoFinger brand. The debut of PotatoFinger Potato Chips is the happy result of their quest for a chip with the perfect combination of crispness and flavor.PotatoFinger is based in Decatur, Georgia.PotatoFinger: How It All BeganPotatoFinger is a favorite nickname from owner Leon Stoltz\'s childhood years in South Africa. A potato chip snacker from an early age, his mom called him "potato fingers" because of the perpetual layer of potato chip residue left behind on his fingers and hands. As a grown-up, he trademarked his nickname, and began the long search for his very own potato chip recipe to manufacture.Introducing... Chipponie!ChipponieWhen PotatoFinger did a search for the right celebrity endorsement of their new potato chip line, they quickly found professional spokesmodel Chipponie and signed her, immediately and indefinitely, to be the "face" of PotatoFinger. Although Chipponie is in high demand for guest slots on several celebrity reality shows, her enthusiasm for PotatoFinger has taken precedence over all of her other projects. She now appears exclusively in promotional work for PotatoFinger. In a recent interview on a well-known late night cable news talk show Chipponie discussed this business relationship at length and summed it up saying "I am sassy. I have attitude. PotatoFinger is an old-school company, distributing chips with attitude! We are a perfect match!"PotatoFinger\'s Mission and ValuesIt is the mission of PotatoFinger to offer an exceptional potato chip to every customer. {'asin': 'B000EIXFAU', 'description': 'PotatoFinger Potato Chips are more than just delicious. They have attitude! They\'re sassy, fresh and appealing, just like the people who enjoy them. Cooked "old school"--thin and crispy, but with no hydrogenated oils or trans fats--PotatoFinger Potato Chips are a new twist on the classic chip, and a healthier alternative to other snacks.It All Starts with the Perfect PotatoPotatoFinger potato chips are made from natural, authentic chipper potatoes. Chipper potatoes are smaller and rounder than baking potatoes, and with less starch and lower sugar. They require a warm, moist climate to yield the highest quality. (A high starch potato turns brown when baked.) During the regular growing season, we use Atlantis potatoes freshly harvested from fields in the eastern US, starting in Florida, ending in late fall with harvests from Ohio. During the winter months we use Snowder potatoes from a greenhouse in Michigan. The potatoes are grown according to US EPA, USDA, and FDA standards. Neither variety is genetically altered.These Chips Win AwardsIn September 2005, PotatoFinger Old School Thin & Crispy Potato Chips was awarded second place in the best snack category in the Best of Atlanta awards at The Atlanta Gourmet Market. Other accolades include Gold Medal Awards from the American Taste Institute of San Francisco and Superior Product Awards from Food Distribution magazine.', 'title': 'PotatoFinger Potato Chips, Salt &amp; Vinegar, 8-Ounce Bags (Pack of 12)', 'imUrl': 'http://ecx.images-amazon.com/images/I/41GX7EAHHKL._SY300_.jpg', 'salesRank': {'Grocery & Gourmet Food': 600321}, 'categories': [['Grocery & Gourmet Food']]}

years ago by Al Jacobson, a visionary who was always several steps ahead of his contemporaries. Joe Hernandez, a Texas native, founded the business with a decade of produce industry experience in a small, rented produce warehouse lunchroom. The original office had one telephone and two chairs--no one could have guessed that, within a few short years, the company would occupy a newly renovated and expanded 280,000 square foot office, warehouse complex, and state-of-the-art CCOF/QAI Certified Organic Packing Facility.World Variety Produce markets product under specially-developed brand names: Melissa\'s, Don Enrique, Rookies, and Jo-San brand. Consumers everywhere recognize the Melissa\'s logo, in cheerful red with a carrot standing in for the letter "I." In 1986, seeking a more inviting label than possible with the World Variety corporate identity, Hernandez named this well-known brand after his daughter. Melissa Hernandez has recently taken an active role in the business. Periodically, she appears at the industry conventions and press events as a company spokesperson--and yes, even in her early 20s, she knows the product line very well.Family is a big part of World Variety&#x92;s success. Through the years, the company has found stable growth thanks to the support of very loyal customers and a close-knit family of employees dedicated to customer service. {'asin': 'B000F4G5V4', 'imUrl': 'http://ecx.images-amazon.com/images/I/41WR8TF16ML._SY300_.jpg', 'description': 'Pringles, which first launched in October 1968, makes its unique snacks using dried potatoes that are cooked and mashed with just enough water and other wholesome ingredients added to form a smooth potato dough. Then, the dough is cut and placed on Pringle-shaped carriers (for that one-of-a-kind shape), fried, and seasoned just right on one side. Then, using special equipment, they\'re stacked into the unique Pringles cans.The Pringles name came about in the late 1960s, when the company made a list of street names from a Cincinnati phone book that began with "P." Pringle Avenue in Finneytown was available for trademark, and its sound appealed to the brand.The first Pringles were packaged in a tall, cylindrical metal can with a red wrapper. The brand expanded nationally in May 1975. Many different flavors and varieties came and went in the 1970s and 1980s, but the most significant breakthrough occurred in September 1996 with the launch of Fat Free Pringles, with P&G;\'s olestra fat substitute.Pringles is a member of the Proctor & Gamble family of brands.About Proctor & GambleTwo billion times a day, Proctor & Gamble brands touch the lives of people around the world. The company has one of the largest and strongest portfolios of trusted brands in the world, including Pampers, Tide, Ariel, Always, Pantene, Bounty, Folgers, Pringles, Charmin, Downy, Iams, Crest, Actonel, and Olay.It all started in 1837 when William Procter and James Gamble settled in Cincinnati. Procter quickly established himself as a candle maker, while Gamble apprenticed himself to a soap maker. The two might never have met had they not married sisters, Olivia and Elizabeth Norris, whose father convinced his new sons-in-law to become business partners. In 1837,a bold new enterprise was born: Procter & Gamble. By each pledging $3,596.47 to the new venture, they began selling soap and candles. Twenty-two years later, their business exceeded $1 million in sales. By 1980 that figure would reach $10 billion, and by 1993 the company would generate over $35 billion in revenue.', 'categories': [['Grocery & Gourmet Food']], 'title': 'Pringles Potato Crisps, Jalapeno, 5.75-Ounce Packages (Pack of 14)'}

Then, the dough is cut and placed on Pringle-shaped carriers (for that one-of-a-kind shape), fried, and seasoned just right on one side. Then, using special equipment, they\'re stacked into the unique Pringles cans.The Pringles name came about in the late 1960s, when the company made a list of street names from a Cincinnati phone book that began with "P." Pringle Avenue in Finneytown was available for trademark, and its sound appealed to the brand.The first Pringles were packaged in a tall, cylindrical metal can with a red wrapper. The brand expanded nationally in May 1975. Many different flavors and varieties came and went in the 1970s and 1980s, but the most significant breakthrough occurred in September 1996 with the launch of Fat Free Pringles, with P&G;\'s olestra fat substitute.Pringles is a member of the Proctor & Gamble family of brands.About Proctor & GambleTwo billion times a day, Proctor & Gamble brands touch the lives of people around the world. The company has one of the largest and strongest portfolios of trusted brands in the world, including Pampers, Tide, Ariel, Always, Pantene, Bounty, Folgers, Pringles, Charmin, Downy, Iams, Crest, Actonel, and Olay.It all started in 1837 when William Procter and James Gamble settled in Cincinnati. Procter quickly established himself as a candle maker, while Gamble apprenticed himself to a soap maker. The two might never have met had they not married sisters, Olivia and Elizabeth Norris, whose father convinced his new sons-in-law to become business partners. In 1837,a bold new enterprise was born: Procter & Gamble. By each pledging $3,596.47 to the new venture, they began selling soap and candles. Twenty-two years later, their business exceeded $1 million in sales. By 1980 that figure would reach $10 billion, and by 1993 the company would generate over $35 billion in revenue.'}

{'asin': 'B000FAGU3G', 'description': 'When A&J;\'s Lasagna Chips\' founder, nutritionist and nurse Elaine Katz, received a call from school nurses that her 5-year-old Jared was hyperactive, it was cause for great distress. At the time, some 30 years ago, the term ADD wasn&#x92;t loosely thrown around as a common explanation for children&#x92;s excited behavior. "It was a big stigma then," Elaine said. Elaine explored natural diets as a means to help her son. Not wanting to take the easy way out through medicine, she sought the help of Dr. Feingold, inventor of the Feingold Diet, which calls for no artificial preservatives or additives in food products. She soon discovered that preservatives such as BHA and BHT found in most snacks would cause her son to bounce off the wall.All-natural supermarkets were non-existent at the time, so finding all-natural snacks was a challenge. This prompted Elaine to create her own snack--a chip made from fresh sheets of lasagna. Using unbleached semolina flour, specially seasoned and cooked, she produced the only all-natural pasta chip with no artificial ingredients, no cholesterol, and 50% less fat than other leading snack chips. Despite the healthy ingredients, this snack became a huge hit among Jared&#x92;s classmates, selling for 10 cents a chip at bake sales and becoming the most popular snack at friends&#x92; parties. Parents loved this new snack, too.In the early \'90s, while living on Long Island, Elaine tried turning her invention into a business. She began making samples out of her garage and received positive response from people tasting it. But, the demands of motherhood proved to be too great to juggle a business as well. It was her now-adult son Jared who recently turned his mother&#x92;s old venture into a reality.', 'title': "A &amp; J's Lasagna Chips, The Wild West Barbecue Flavor, 5-Ounce Bags (Pack of 12)", 'imUrl': 'http://ecx.images-amazon.com/images/I/51XC2T0904L._SY300_.jpg', 'salesRank': {'Grocery & Gourmet Food': 450527}, 'categories': [['Grocery & Gourmet Food']]}

Mariani, Jr., developed, for the first time, a moist dried fruit product that did not have to be rehydrated at home. Through this innovation, the business grew and perfected working partnerships with major supermarkets throughout the country.In 1979, Paul Mariani Sr.'s grandson, Mark A. Mariani, became responsible for its legacy. From the company's solid foundation, he has grown the business and the company now sells more than 125 million pounds of product annually. {'asin': 'B001TOTG9C', 'description': 'Grown in the tropical areas of Ecuador, South America, Tropic Max selected plantains are carefully harvested by hand, sliced and delicately golden-crisped to create a delicious, nutritious tropical fruit chip, Rich in Potassium, Fiber, Vitamin A and Vitamin C, no cholesterol, artificial colors, flavors, or added preservatives.Try them as a naturally healthy great tasting tropical snack.What is a Plantain ?Plantains are similar to bananas. In fact, they are considered the cousin of the banana. However, Anyone who has ever accidentally eaten plantains instead of bananas will most likely not have a problem telling the two fruits apart. If bananas are the dessert, then plantains would be the mashed potatoes. Plantains look very similar to their sweeter banana cousins, but they are much starchier in consistency and blander in taste. Plantains grow in the same tropical regions as bananas, but they are not used for the same culinary purposes.Some sources suggest that plantains should never be eaten raw or in their unripened green stage. Others say that plantains can be eaten throughout their entire ripening period, but must be prepared properly for their changing taste and texture. Plantains in their earliest stages have a green skin which cannot be peeled off easily. Cooks using plantains at this stage often cut them into two inch (5 cm) sections and boil them until they are the consistency of boiled potatoes.As plantains continue to ripen, they become more of a yellow-orange than their bright yellow banana counterparts. They are still not sweet, but their flavor is not as bland as during the green stage. Finally, plantains ripen to a dark black color just before spoiling. Plantains at the overripe stage are almost as sweet as bananas, and can be peeled by hand. Shoppers looking for a different kind of banana for cooking should consider buying these black-skinned plantains.', 'title': 'Tropic Max Spicy Plantain Chips - 3 oz', 'imUrl': 'http://ecx.images-amazon.com/images/I/51qU2w89XlL._SY300_.jpg', 'salesRank': {'Grocery & Gourmet Food': 430264}, 'categories': [['Grocery & Gourmet Food']]}
